Editorial Reviews

About the Author

Adrian Ostrowski is a modern C++ enthusiast interested in the development of both the C++ language itself and the high-quality code written in it. A lifelong learner with over a decade of experience in the IT industry and more than 8 years of experience with C++ specifically, he's always eager to share his knowledge. His past projects range from parallel computing, through fiber networking, to working on a commodity exchange's trading system. Currently, he's one of the architects of Intel and Habana's integration with machine learning frameworks.

In his spare time, Adrian used to promote music bands together with Piotr and has learned how to fly a glider. Currently, he likes riding his bicycle, going to music events, and browsing memes.

Piotr Gaczkowski has more than 10 years of experience in programming and practicing DevOps and uses his skills to improve people's lives. He likes building simple solutions to human problems, organizing cultural events, and teaching fellow professionals. Piotr is keen on automating boring activities and using his experience to share knowledge by conducting courses and writing articles about personal growth and remote work.

He has worked in the IT industry both in full-time positions and as a freelancer, but his true passion is music. When not making his skills useful at work, you can find him building communities.

--This text refers to the paperback edition.

the_real_diane
4.0 out of 5 stars Disappointing
Reviewed in the United States on June 30, 2021
Verified Purchase
I was expecting to see aspects of software architecture that are influenced by the C++20 standard and new architectural patterns that are enabled by it. What I got was a mishmash -- the book isn't really about software architecture as much as it is about implementation -- so on the one hand it's useful if you want to Java-ize your code but on the other hand there's a lot of handwaving rather than concrete description when it comes to new standard features such as modules.

My viewpoint is influenced by needing to maintain and enhance portions of a very large service that needs to be modernized in an incremental fashion due to its size and overall complexity. The architectural challenges are significant and this book is not particularly helpful.

Fedor G. Pikus
5.0 out of 5 stars Very useful and practical book on software architecture
Reviewed in the United States on April 28, 2021
It's hard to write books on software design and architecture. Many design books are filled with general principles and platitudes, while others cover mostly coding techniques (useful but falls short of the architecture level). This book skillfully threads the middle ground: it is firmly rooted in practical software development, but the discussion inevitably raises to the level of the general practices and architecture.

The overall emphasis is definitely on "effective concepts," but it's not a dry reading. Every chapter presents a realistic problem and discusses effective programming practices, coding techniques, and design guidelines.

While the software architecture, in general, is language-agnostic, the practical nature of this book means that the authors select concepts and practices that best map onto the paradigms and constructs available in the C++ language. Overall, I highly recommend this book for any C++ programmer.

Jeff Szuhay
5.0 out of 5 stars A complete overview of all aspects of building a modern distributed system
Reviewed in the United States on May 2, 2021
This provides thorough overview of and practical guidance for all aspects of building a modern distributed system for the intermediate to advanced C++ programmer.

Building a modern distributed system is not just about designing the system; it is also about ensuring a accurate, reliable, and complete implementation of that system.

This book focuses on all aspects of the design and implementation considerations to build a successful distributed system. It begins with a presentation of a variety of design approaches, such as stateful and stateless services, monolithic services versus microservices, layered architectures and module-bases architectures. Guidance on gathering and documenting requirements is covered. Many aspects of implementing the system in C++ are illuminated. Most significantly, the oft-overlooked concepts of testability, performance, scalability, and security. I was particularly pleased to see a practical discussion of code review during system development.

The last chapters of the book takes a deeper dive on various architectures such as microservices, containers, web services, and cloud-native services. For each architecture, it provides useful tools and practical approaches for implementation and deployment.

For any programmer who is individually or on a team responsible for developing, deploying,
and/or maintaining a distributed system, this book is an indispensable guide to success.

Kelvin D. Meeks
5.0 out of 5 stars Master Class in Software Architecture with C++
Reviewed in the United States on May 5, 2021
Imagine spending thousands of dollars to attend some of the best world-class conferences. In addition to the cost of the conference, you will also incur travel costs, hotels, meals, parking, and the costs of the time spent being away from your fulltime job. While attending such conferences – you have the opportunity to sit in on sessions – presented by leading practitioners – but you will be challenged to decide which sessions to select – and you will inevitably have to miss out on some when choices must be made. Embodied in this book are some of the most important lessons that you might glean from attending several such conferences. The additional value of this book – is that it is concisely written – and in the latter chapters, provides a specialized focus through the lens of Software Architecture with C++. However, many of the lessons conveyed in its pages are applicable, regardless of your language choice. By learning C++ you will become a better programmer. Period. You will have a deeper understanding of the underlying design and performance considerations of all programming languages – and you will have added a powerful tool to your toolbox.

This book is the equivalent of a Master Class in Software Architecture with C++

Pavel Roskin
5.0 out of 5 stars Engaging, comprehensive, highly useful
Reviewed in the United States on May 29, 2021
The book is surprisingly broad in its scope, it covers almost every aspect of software architecture I have encountered during my career. Some terms used in the book were unfamiliar to me, yet they formalize the principles I’ve been following intuitively. This book helped me understand those principles and gave me vocabulary to explain it to others.
The authors are very good at illustrating common guiding principles with practical code examples, yet those examples are short and to the point. In particular, the explanation of every letter in SOLID is brilliant, I would recommend it to every developer I work with. Likewise, the C++ specific rules are covered in great detail.
The authors are careful not to suggest “the one true way”; they let the reader decide, often providing references to other publications.
Even though most use cases cover network services, I appreciate that the authors covered fault tolerant systems that are so useful in aerospace.
This book is not a C++ textbook. A good knowledge of C++ is required to use the book effectively. Rather, this book can help a Senior software developer become a Principal or a Software Architect.
